You are working on an institutional-grade portfolio analytics proof-of-work project.

Project:
MF Risk Diagnostic Module

Final public artifact:
Streamlit-first webapp, supported by an Excel model of record, Power BI screenshot deck, GitHub README, Notion methodology, and LinkedIn carousel.

Data approach:
API-first. The user will not manually input NAV or TRI data. Mutual fund NAV data and benchmark/index data must be fetched programmatically and cached locally.

Core rule:
The Streamlit app must read processed CSVs. It must not make live API calls on every page load.

Rules:
1. Do not invent data.
2. Do not hardcode final outputs.
3. Do not require manual NAV/TRI file input for normal execution.
4. MFAPI is used for automated mutual fund NAV extraction.
5. Benchmark/index data must be fetched programmatically and cached.
6. Do not silently label price-index proxies as TRI.
7. Yahoo/yfinance fallbacks must be labelled as price-index proxies, not TRI.
8. Every metric must disclose formula, frequency, interpretation, and limitation.
9. Daily and monthly returns must not be mixed incorrectly.
10. Benchmarks must be fund-specific.
11. VaR and CVaR must be labelled by frequency.
12. Stress-test assumptions must be labelled illustrative, not forecasts.
13. Every chart must answer an investment question.
14. Every page must end with interpretation, not just visuals.
15. Keep code modular.
16. Do not modify more than 3 files at once unless explicitly asked.
17. Never rewrite the full repo unless explicitly requested.
18. Keep model auditability higher priority than UI decoration.
19. Maintain README, data dictionary, assumptions log, formula audit, model governance, and limitations files.
20. If uncertain about a financial formula or benchmark source, stop and ask before implementing.